~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Notes Specific to Apple's macOS
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

.. include:: prologue.rst

.. contents::

Overview
========

This document describes platform-specific behaviour, build requirements,
and workarounds relevant when running BRLTTY on macOS.

Building from Source
====================

BRLTTY must be built from source on macOS.  Configure with
``--prefix=/usr/local`` so that the install targets do not attempt to write
to the read-only root filesystem (``/``):

.. code-block:: bash

   ./configure --prefix=/usr/local
   make -j4
   sudo make install

The build requires Xcode Command Line Tools (``xcode-select --install``) and
the following Homebrew packages:

* ``pkg-config`` â€” for locating library headers and flags
* ``liblouis`` â€” braille translation tables (optional but recommended)
* ``espeak-ng`` â€” speech synthesis (optional)

Running as Root
===============

BRLTTY needs root privileges to open USB and serial braille devices.
``brltty-term`` uses ``sudo`` to start BRLTTY.

If you are using the optional Hammerspoon automation (see `Hammerspoon
Automation`_ below), a sudoers template is installed by
``sudo make install-hammerspoon`` at
``/usr/local/share/brltty/Autostart/Hammerspoon/sudoers.brltty``.
Edit it to replace ``username`` with the account that will run ``brltty-term``,
then install it::

   sudo cp /usr/local/share/brltty/Autostart/Hammerspoon/sudoers.brltty \
           /etc/sudoers.d/brltty
   sudo visudo -cf /etc/sudoers.d/brltty

The ``SETENV`` flag is required because ``brltty-term`` passes the user
environment to BRLTTY via ``sudo --preserve-env``.

BRLTTY Configuration
====================

A minimal ``/usr/local/etc/brltty.conf`` for a USB braille display::

   braille-driver NAME
   braille-device usb:
   api-parameters auth=none

Replace ``NAME`` with the two-letter driver code for your display
(e.g. ``fs`` for Freedom Scientific, ``ht`` for Handy Tech).

The ``api-parameters auth=none`` line disables BrlAPI key-file authentication.
The default key file is empty on a fresh macOS install, which causes the
server to reject connections; disabling authentication works around this.

The screen driver (``-xem``) is set on the command line by ``brltty-term``
and should not be set in ``brltty.conf``.

Sharing the Braille Display with VoiceOver
==========================================

VoiceOver and BRLTTY both require exclusive access to a USB braille display;
macOS does not allow two applications to hold the same USB device
simultaneously.  There are two ways to use them together:

**BRLTTY for braille, VoiceOver for speech only**
   Start BRLTTY before starting VoiceOver.  BRLTTY claims the USB device
   first; VoiceOver finds it already taken and falls back to text-to-speech
   only.  No additional software is needed.  Braille output is always driven
   by BRLTTY; VoiceOver provides speech in GUI applications alongside it.

**Automatic handoff: braille follows focus** *(optional, requires Hammerspoon)*
   If you want braille output in GUI applications via VoiceOver *and* in the
   terminal via BRLTTY, the display must transfer between the two whenever
   you switch focus.  Hammerspoon_ â€” a free macOS automation app that is not
   part of BRLTTY and must be installed separately â€” can do this
   automatically: when you switch to the terminal emulator, VoiceOver quits
   and BRLTTY reclaims the display; when you switch away, BRLTTY suspends
   and VoiceOver restarts.

   The switch takes a few seconds in the BRLTTY direction because VoiceOver
   must fully release the USB device before BRLTTY can open it.

brltty-handoff
--------------

``brltty-handoff`` is a small utility that tells a running BRLTTY to release
or reclaim the braille device via BrlAPI.  It is used by the Hammerspoon
automation script but can also be called directly:

``brltty-handoff suspend``
   Causes BRLTTY to release the USB device.  Forks a background worker that
   holds the BrlAPI connection open (keeping the driver suspended) and writes
   the worker PID to ``/tmp/brltty-handoff.pid``.

``brltty-handoff resume``
   Signals the background worker to resume the driver and exit.  If no
   worker is running the command is a no-op.

The background worker is necessary because the braille driver stays suspended
only while a BrlAPI connection remains open.

Hammerspoon Automation
----------------------

Hammerspoon_ is a free, open-source macOS automation app that exposes
system events (application focus changes, hotkeys, etc.) to a Lua scripting
interface.  BRLTTY ships an optional Hammerspoon configuration
(``Autostart/Hammerspoon/brltty.lua``) that implements the automatic handoff
described above.  It is not required and does not need to be installed unless
you want braille output in both the terminal and GUI applications.

**Prerequisites**

Before installing the BRLTTY Hammerspoon script:

1. Install Hammerspoon: ``brew install --cask hammerspoon``
2. Grant Hammerspoon Accessibility permission in
   System Settings â†’ Privacy & Security â†’ Accessibility
3. In VoiceOver Utility â†’ General, enable
   "Allow VoiceOver to be controlled with AppleScript"

**Installing the BRLTTY Hammerspoon script**

::

   sudo make install-hammerspoon

This installs ``brltty.lua`` to
``/usr/local/share/brltty/Autostart/Hammerspoon/``.

**If Hammerspoon is not yet configured** on your machine, symlink ``brltty.lua``
as your Hammerspoon entry point::

   ln -s /usr/local/share/brltty/Autostart/Hammerspoon/brltty.lua \
         ~/.hammerspoon/init.lua

**If you already have a** ``~/.hammerspoon/init.lua``, copy ``brltty.lua``
into your Hammerspoon directory and load it from your existing config::

   cp /usr/local/share/brltty/Autostart/Hammerspoon/brltty.lua \
      ~/.hammerspoon/brltty.lua

Then add the following line to your ``~/.hammerspoon/init.lua``::

   require("brltty")

The active terminal emulator is detected automatically by walking up
BRLTTY's process ancestry (brltty â†’ sudo â†’ shell â†’ terminal app), so no
hardcoded application name is needed.  ``TERMINAL_BUNDLES`` near the top
of ``brltty.lua`` is a fallback allowlist used before BRLTTY has started;
extend it if you use a terminal emulator not listed there.

How the Handoff Works
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

When **the terminal emulator gains focus**:

1. Hammerspoon confirms the focused app is the terminal running brltty
   (via process ancestry detection or the ``TERMINAL_BUNDLES`` fallback).
2. Hammerspoon polls every 0.5 s until BRLTTY is confirmed running.
3. VoiceOver is told to quit via AppleScript (clean shutdown, releases USB).
4. Hammerspoon waits until both VoiceOver and BrailleTranslationService
   have exited.
5. ``brltty-handoff resume`` is called so BRLTTY reclaims the display.

When **the terminal emulator loses focus**:

1. ``brltty-handoff suspend`` is called synchronously.
2. VoiceOver is started via VoiceOverStarter.

The ``HANDOFF_COOLDOWN`` (3 s) suppresses the spurious "away from terminal"
event that macOS fires when VoiceOver emits its startup announcement.

The automation triggers on any focus change away from the terminal â€”
including system dialogs and permission prompts â€” so a blind user is never
left without braille output unexpectedly.  One current limitation: focus
changes *within* the terminal app itself (e.g. a native dialog spawned by
iTerm2) are not detected, since Hammerspoon's app-switch events do not
cover intra-application focus changes.

While VoiceOver is off (during terminal use), macOS "Speak announcements"
(System Settings â†’ Accessibility â†’ Spoken Content â†’ Speak announcements)
is enabled automatically so that system notifications are still read aloud.
It is restored when VoiceOver resumes.

Technical Notes
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

VoiceOver's braille support runs in a separate XPC process called
``BrailleTranslationService``.  After VoiceOver quits, this process
continues to hold the USB device for a few seconds; BRLTTY must wait for
it to exit before opening the device.  If VoiceOver Utility (the
configuration app) is open, it keeps ``BrailleTranslationService`` alive
indefinitely â€” the Hammerspoon config detects this and quits VoiceOver
Utility automatically before starting the handoff.

Killing VoiceOver with ``SIGTERM`` or ``SIGKILL`` leaves the IOKit USB
seize unreleased for 60 seconds or more.  The Hammerspoon config always
quits VoiceOver via AppleScript (``tell application "VoiceOver" to quit``),
which triggers a clean shutdown and releases the device promptly.

Clipboard
=========

``brltty-pty`` supports clipboard modes configured via the
``BRLTTY_PTY_CLIPBOARD_MODE`` environment variable:

``auto`` *(default)*
   ``brltty-pty`` probes the outer terminal for OSC 52 support and picks
   ``passthrough`` or ``native`` accordingly.

``passthrough``
   ``brltty-pty`` forwards OSC 52 sequences to the outer terminal.  Works
   with iTerm2, kitty, WezTerm, and most modern terminal emulators.

``native``
   ``brltty-pty`` writes directly to the macOS clipboard via AppKit.
   Use this for Apple Terminal.app, which does not support OSC 52.

Troubleshooting
===============

**Terminal shows blank on braille display**
   BRLTTY is using ``poll(2)`` instead of ``select(2)`` to monitor the PTY
   master.  On macOS ``poll(2)`` does not report activity on PTY or character
   devices; ``select(2)`` must be used instead.  Ensure the macOS fix in
   ``Programs/async_io.c`` is included in the build and reinstall BRLTTY.

**brltty-term prompts for a password**
   The sudoers entry is missing or lacks ``SETENV``.  Reinstall
   ``/etc/sudoers.d/brltty`` with the entry shown above.

**make install fails with "Read-only file system"**
   ``configure`` was run without ``--prefix=/usr/local``.  Re-run configure
   with the correct prefix, rebuild, and reinstall.

**Display not connecting after VoiceOver quits**
   Wait for ``BrailleTranslationService`` to exit (up to ~5 s).  The
   Hammerspoon config handles this automatically.

.. _Hammerspoon: https://www.hammerspoon.org/
